algol designated beta persei persei abbreviated beta per per known colloquially as the demon star is bright multiple star in the constellation of perseus it is the first and best known eclipsing binary and one of the first non nova variable stars to be discovered it is three star system consisting of beta persei aa aa and ab in which the large and bright primary persei aa is regularly eclipsed by the dimmer persei aa thus algol magnitude is usually near constant at but regularly dips to every days days hours and minutes during the roughly hour long partial eclipses there is also secondary eclipse the second minimum when the brighter star occults the fainter secondary this secondary eclipse can only be detected algol gives its name to its class of eclipsing variable known as algol variables observation history the algol system on august this is chara interferometer image with milliarcsecond resolution in the near infrared band the elongated appearance of algol aa labelled and the round appearance of algol aa labelled are real but the form of algol ab labelled is an artifact an ancient egyptian calendar of lucky and unlucky days composed some years ago is claimed to be the oldest historical document of the discovery of algol the association of algol with demon like creature gorgon in the greek tradition ghoul in the arabic tradition suggests that its variability was known long before the th century but except for the ancient egyptian discovery there is still no indisputable evidence for this the variability of algol was noted in by italian astronomer geminiano montanari but the periodic nature of its variations in brightness was not recognized until more than century later when the british amateur astronomer john goodricke also proposed mechanism for the star variability in may he presented his findings to the royal society suggesting that the periodic variability was caused by dark body passing in front of the star or else that the star itself has darker region that is periodically turned toward the earth for his report he was awarded the copley medal in the harvard astronomer edward charles pickering presented evidence that algol was actually an eclipsing binary this was confirmed few years later in when the potsdam astronomer hermann carl vogel found periodic doppler shifts in the spectrum of algol inferring variations in the radial velocity of this binary system thus algol became one of the first known spectroscopic binaries joel stebbins at the university of illinois observatory used an early selenium cell photometer to produce the first ever photoelectric study of variable star the light curve revealed the second minimum and the reflection effect between the two stars some difficulties in explaining the observed spectroscopic features led to the conjecture that third star may be present in the system four decades later this conjecture was found to be correct system chara interferometer in the near infrared band sorted according to orbital phase because some phases are poorly covered aa jumps at some points along its path interpolation of the orbit of aa around aa with focus on aa from the point of view of the earth algol aa and algol aa form an eclipsing binary because their orbital plane contains the line of sight to the earth to be more precise algol is triple star system the eclipsing binary pair is separated by only astronomical units au from each other whereas the third star in the system algol ab is at an average distance of au from the pair and the mutual orbital period of the trio is earth days the total mass of the system is about solar masses and the mass ratios of aa aa and ab are about to to the three components of the bright triple star used to be and still sometimes are referred to as per and the washington double star catalog lists them as aa aa and an with two very faint stars and about one arcmin distant further five faint stars are also listed as companions studies of algol led to the algol paradox in the theory of stellar evolution although components of binary star form at the same time and massive stars evolve much faster than the less massive stars the more massive component algol is still in the main sequence but the less massive algol is subgiant star at later evolutionary stage the paradox can be solved by mass transfer when the more massive star became subgiant it filled its roche lobe and most of the mass was transferred to the other star which is still in the main sequence in some binaries similar to algol gas flow can be seen this system also exhibits ray and radio wave flares the ray flares are thought to be caused by the magnetic fields of the and components interacting with the mass transfer the radio wave flares might be created by magnetic cycles similar to those of sunspots but because the magnetic fields of these stars are up to ten times stronger than the field of the sun these radio flares are more powerful and more persistent magnetic activity cycles in the active secondary component induce changes in its radius of gyration that have been linked to recurrent orbital period variations on the order of via the applegate mechanism mass transfer between the components is small in the algol system but could be significant source of period change in other algol type binaries algol is about light years from the sun but about million years ago it passed within light years of the solar system and its apparent magnitude was about which is considerably brighter than the star sirius is today because the total mass of the algol system is about solar masses at the closest approach this might have given enough gravity to perturb the oort cloud of the solar system somewhat and hence increase the number of comets entering the inner solar system however the actual increase in net cometary collisions is thought to have been quite small names beta persei is the star bayer designation the name algol derives from arabic raʾs al ghūl head raʾs of the ogre al ghūl see ghoul the english name demon star is direct translation of this in the international astronomical union organized working group on star names wgsn to catalog and standardize proper names for stars the wgsn first bulletin of july included table of the first two batches of names approved by the wgsn which included algol for this star it is so entered on the iau catalog of star names in hebrew folklore algol was called rōsh ha sāṭān or satan head as stated by edmund chilmead who called it divels head or rosch hassatan latin name for algol from the th century was caput larvae or the spectre head hipparchus and pliny made this separate though connected constellation in chinese meaning mausoleum refers to an asterism consisting of persei persei persei persei persei persei persei and persei consequently persei itself is known as english the fifth star of mausoleum according to allen the star bore the grim name of tseih she meaning piled up corpses but this appears to be and dié shī is correctly persei which is inside the mausoleum cultural significance historically the star has received strong association with bloody violence across wide variety of cultures in the tetrabiblos the nd century astrological text of the alexandrian astronomer ptolemy algol is referred to as the gorgon of perseus and associated with death by decapitation theme which mirrors the myth of the hero perseus victory over the snake haired gorgon medusa astrologically algol is considered one of the unluckiest stars in the sky and was listed as one of the behenian stars see also algol in fiction references external links
