amalasuntha also known as amalasuentha amalaswintha amalasuintha amalswinthe amalasontha or amalsenta april was regent of the ostrogoths from to she was the youngest daughter of theoderic the great and firmly believed in the upholding of roman virtues and values she is best known for her diplomatic relationship with justinian who would invade italy in response to her assassination life in amalasuntha married eutharic an ostrogoth noble of the old amali dynasty who had been previously living in the arian kingdom of hispania her husband was the son of widerich born grandson of berismund born and great grandson of thorismund died after king of the ostrogoths it was important to amalasuntha father theoderic the great that she marry into legitimate royal family lest her own family legitimacy be questioned she was very much an intellectual and was well known for her extensive knowledge which included the study of three languages latin greek and gothic in addition she was student of philosophy and was said to possess the wisdom of solomon amalasuntha was also described in her day as possessing all of the central roman virtues expected of noble woman happiness fertility and patience although more emphasis was placed on her virtues within the political realm versus the feminine something that separates her from other ostrogoth princesses regent her husband died apparently in the early years of her marriage leaving her with two children athalaric and matasuntha after wife of germanus on the death of her father on august her son succeeded him at the age of ten but she held the power as regent for her son her tremendous influence in her position as regent can be seen in diptych she appears in alongside her son athalaric in deeply imbued with the old roman culture she gave to that son education more refined and literary turn than suited the ideas of her gothic subjects conscious of her unpopularity she banished and afterwards put to death three gothic nobles whom she suspected of conspiring against her rule at the same time she opened negotiations with the byzantine emperor justinian with the view of removing herself and the gothic treasure to constantinople her son death in made little change in the posture of affairs monarch after athalaric death amalasuntha became queen ruling independently only for short while before making her cousin theodahad partner of her throne not as sometimes stated her husband for his wife was still living with the intent of strengthening her position theodahad was prominent leader of the gothic military aristocracy the very group that so opposed her pro roman stances amalasuntha believed this pairing would help to make supporters out of her harshest critics the choice was unfortunate for theodahad fostered the disaffection of the goths and either by his orders or with his permission amalasuntha was imprisoned in the island of martana in the tuscan lake of bolsena where on april in the spring of she was murdered in her bath death the death of amalasuntha would give justinian reason to go to war with the ostrogoths and attempt to take italy according to the eastern roman historian procopius it is believed that amalasuntha and justinian had very close diplomatic relationship more specifically procopius believed that amalasuntha was thinking about handing over italy to justinian around the time of her death shortly after amalasuntha murder theodahad was replaced by witigis amalasuntha son in law with the people support witigis had theodahad put to death sources the letters of cassiodorus chief minister and literary adviser of amalasuntha and the histories of procopius and jordanes give us our chief information as to the character of amalasuntha cassiodorus was part of greater pro roman party that desired to romanize the traditional ostrogothic kingship further evidence of the pro roman circle that amalasuntha surrounded herself with fiction the life of amalasuntha was made the subject of tragedy the first play written by the young carlo goldoni and presented at milan in legacy asteroid amalasuntha is named in her honour references
afonso kg january august called the african was king of portugal and of the algarves his sobriquet refers to his conquests in northern africa as of afonso was the first king of portugal to claim dominion over plural kingdom of the algarves instead of the singular kingdom of the algarve territories added to the portuguese crown lands in north africa during the th century came to be referred to as possessions of the kingdom of the algarve now region of southern portugal not the kingdom of portugal the algarves then were considered to be the southern portuguese territories on both sides of the strait of gibraltar early life afonse of portugal afonso was born in sintra the eldest son of king edward of portugal by his wife eleanor of aragon afonso was only six years old when he succeeded his father in during his minority afonso was placed under the regency of his mother in accordance with will of his late father as both foreigner and woman the queen was not popular choice for regent opposition rose and without any important ally among the portuguese aristocracy other than afonso count of barcelos the illegitimate half brother of king edward the queen position was untenable in the portuguese cortes assembly of the kingdom decided to replace the queen with peter duke of coimbra dom pedro the young king oldest uncle peter main policies were concerned with restricting the political power of the great noble houses and expanding the powers of the crown the country prospered under his rule but not peacefully as his laws interfered with the ambition of powerful nobles the count of barcelos personal enemy of the duke of coimbra despite being half brothers eventually became the king favourite uncle and began constant struggle for power in the king made afonso the first duke of braganza with this title and its lands he became the most powerful man in portugal and one of the richest men in europe to secure his position as regent peter had afonso marry his daughter isabella of coimbra in but on june when the king came of age peter had to surrender his power to afonso the years of conspiracy by the duke of braganza finally came to head on september of the same year afonso nullified all the laws and edicts approved under the regency in the following year led by what were later discovered to be false accusations afonso declared peter rebel and defeated his army in the battle of alfarrobeira in which his uncle and father in law was killed after this battle and the loss of one of portugal most remarkable infantes the duke of braganza became the de facto ruler of the country invasion of morocco afonso then turned his attentions to north africa in the reign of his grandfather john ceuta had been conquered from the king of morocco and now the new king wanted to expand the conquests the king army conquered alcácer ceguer in and arzila in tangiers on the other hand was won and lost several times between and these achievements granted the king the nickname of the african or africano the king also supported the exploration of the atlantic ocean led by prince henry the navigator but after henry death in he did nothing to continue henry work afonso was passive king he chose not to pursue the revision of laws or development of commerce preferring instead to preserve the legacy of his father edward and grandfather john in pope nicholas issued the papal bull dum diversas which granted afonso the right to reduce saracens pagans and any other unbelievers to hereditary slavery this was reaffirmed and extended in the romanus pontifex bull of also by nicholas these papal bulls came to be seen by some as justification for the subsequent era of slave trade and european colonialism copy of the fra mauro map was made under commission by afonso in finished on april it was sent to portugal with letter to prince henry the navigator afonso uncle encouraging further funding of exploration trips although the copy has been lost the andrea bianco original is preserved at the biblioteca marciana venice when the campaigns in africa were over afonso found new grounds for battle in neighboring castile on december king henry iv of castile died without male heir leaving from his two marriages only daughter joanna la beltraneja but her paternity was questioned it was rumored that his queen joan of portugal had an affair with nobleman named beltrán de la cueva the birth of princess joanna in openly called la beltraneja caused the separation of her parents she was never considered legitimate and when the king was dying no one took her as serious contender for the crown her father half sister the future queen isabella of castile was due to inherit the crown but afonso was persuaded to intervene in the succession in he married his niece joanna whom he considered the legitimate heir to the crown he proclaimed himself king of castile and león and prepared to defend his wife rights after the indecisive battle of toro in against king ferdinand ii of aragon the husband of isabella of castile afonso went to france to obtain the assistance of king louis xi but finding himself deceived by the french monarch he returned to portugal in disillusioned he abdicated for few days in november in favor of his son john ii then after returning to the throne he retired to monastery in sintra where he died in marriages and descendants afonso married firstly in with isabella of coimbra with whom he had three children john prince of portugal january joan princess of portugal february may known as saint joan of portugal or saint joan princess john ii of portugal march october succeeded his father as th king of portugal afonso married secondly in with joanna of castile known as la beltraneja but no children were born of this marriage ancestry notes references miller townsend the battle of toro in history today volume
